Should I keep on call?

While you're in the Djibouti, get tested for HIV/AIDS, tuberculosis, malaria and other infectious diseases. Your provider can give you a prescription for medicines to protect you from these diseases.

For HIV, the CDC recommends using Pre-Exposure Prophylaxis (PrEP). PrEP (pre-exposure prophylaxis) is when people at very high risk for HIV take HIV medicine daily to lower their chances of getting infected. Your HIV-negative status and sexual practices will impact whether or not PrEP is the right choice for you.

Always leave extra time to get back to the hospital.

How can I stay safe?

Once you have your vaccination, you can safely live and travel to Djibouti.

Be sure you have travel insurance that covers doctor's visits, hospital stays and emergency medical services. Ask your provider if he or she accepts Travel Guardians insurance.

Most importantly, pack the medical kit listed above, and check the expiration dates of the medicines. Pack anything else you usually use when you're sick, like first-aid creams. It's smart to keep copies of your prescriptions in case you need them.

No vaccinations are required or recommended for travelers to Djibouti.
